data.content:
Your assertions work but produce poor failure messages. Modern MSTest has specialized collection assertions that tell you *what* went wrong:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);                          // instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));         // no built-in "all match" assert, this one is fine
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);                         // instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users); // or just:
}
```

**Key changes:**

| Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" vs generic "expected true" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows expected vs actual count |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | Keep `Assert.IsTrue` for the predicate check, or extract and use `Assert.IsNotNull` |

For the admin check specifically:

```csharp
// Option A: if there should be exactly one admin
var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
Assert.IsTrue(admin.IsActive);

// Option B: just verify presence
Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
```

`Assert.ContainsSingle` returns the element, so you can chain further assertions on it. These APIs are available in **MSTest 3.x+**.
